03964nam a22006015i 9780231540469DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20162016nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2015010548  a(OCoLC)984686823  a97802315404697 a10.7312/meis166322doi  a(DE-B1597)468906  a(OCoLC)936117829  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aPN45b.M433 2016 4aPN45 7aLIT0060002bisacsh04a8012231 aMeisel, Martin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aChaos Imagined :bLiterature, Art, Science /cMartin Meisel. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (608 p.) :b96 b&w illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tΩ. Uncertainty and Complexity -- t1. Shaping Chaos -- t2. Nothing and Something -- t3. Number -- t4. Carnival -- t5. War -- t6. Energy -- t7. Entropy -- t8. Coda, Or Da Capo Al Fine -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe stories we tell in our attempt to make sense of the world—our myths and religion, literature and philosophy, science and art—are the comforting vehicles we use to transmit ideas of order. But beneath the quest for order lies the uneasy dread of fundamental disorder. True chaos is hard to imagine and even harder to represent. In this book, Martin Meisel considers the long effort to conjure, depict, and rationalize extreme disorder, with all the passion, excitement, and compromises the act provokes.Meisel builds a rough history from major social, psychological, and cosmological turning points in the imagining of chaos. He uses examples from literature, philosophy, painting, graphic art, science, linguistics, music, and film, particularly exploring the remarkable shift in the eighteenth and nineteenth centuries from conceiving of chaos as disruptive to celebrating its liberating and energizing potential. Discussions of Sophocles, Plato, Lucretius, Calderon, Milton, Haydn, Blake, Faraday, Chekhov, Faulkner, Wells, and Beckett, among others, are matched with incisive readings of art by Brueghel, Rubens, Goya, Turner, Dix, Dada, and the futurists. Meisel addresses the revolution in mapping energy and entropy and the manifold effect of thermodynamics. He then uses this chaotic frame to elaborate on purpose, mortality, meaning, and mind.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aArts and society. 0aChaotic behavior in systems in literature. 0aChaotic behavior in systemsxSocial aspects. 0aEntropy in literature. 0aLiterature and science. 0aLiterature and society. 0aSocial change. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Semiotics & Theory.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311063857840uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/meis1663240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231540469423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231540469/original  a978-3-11-063857-8  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles